Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have likened the Japanese earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear catastrophe to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: each of these activities generates large profits and includes a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crises ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a century flood, combined with defects in design that are usually harmless, caused the shutdown of the cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In terms of financial markets, an unanticipated collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivative and repo markets, has damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
Although base risks originate outside of systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, over-investment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and bad luck ensured that systems were unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a credit freeze on markets for several long weeks.
We now understand the risks and design flaws of Fukushima quite well.
We cannot say the same of the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
A Fukushima, the teams of workers are bravely trying to stop the radiation leaks.
On the other hand, for derivatives, similar efforts are poorly directed and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are re-creating similar derivatives and financial structures, on top of the same active errors.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of the euro's fluctuation but does not want the risk on the yen, while for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros by June 1st, and the second promises to provide yens.
If a currency loses value relative to another, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as treasury bonds or mortgage debt, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase – or buy back, ndt).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheet of the largest financial institutions, which implies that simple financial tremors can affect them strongly.
Some institutions may then be deprived of repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, such as Bear Stearns.
Individual transactions, on derivatives or repos, are hardly blameworthy.
Each one separately transfers the risk in a legitimate way to those who are better suited to bear it, or allows financial participation.
However, when they are excessively used by institutions that are vital at the systemic level, they can blow up the financial system due to its design flaws.
Even today, almost 70% of the main liabilities of American financial companies are made up of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most common constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors holding derivatives or repo contracts with financially fragile institutions can seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide its fate while, with a little more time, the company in question could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos find themselves at the head of the reimbursement queue in so many ways, they have less incentive to encourage market discipline by closely verifying the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be reimbursed, anyway.
Surely, someone has to be first.
Other financial actors must take on more risk because the exemptions for derivatives and repo players put them at the forefront in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect the others to therefore have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that follows in the line is too often the American government, as a guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too big to let them go bankrupt, ndt). However, the government is not well-placed to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often limits itself to regulated markets; and, when economic conditions are good, no official wants to spoil the party.
The US Congress had an opportunity to solve this flaw in the major remake of finance it adopted last summer via the Dodd Frank bill.
The government didn't seize it.
If investors in derivatives, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit event derivatives, ndt) were not given favorable treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would demand capitalization of their counterparties more frequently.
They accepted the risk generated by ultra-low capitalizations when it was essentially about U.S. government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it was their own money at stake.
The public perceives risks of the type Fukushima and risks associated with derivatives differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must face security concerns.
But the markets for derivatives and repos present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract the public's attention and disdain, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding the risks of the type Fukushima, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built in a way to contain the risks of earthquakes and tsunamis thanks to passive cooling systems.
It is considered possible today to predict nuclear power plants capable of keeping the fuel rods cold even in the event of a complete power outage.
On the other hand, few significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damage that the priority of derivative products and repos in case of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require end-users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect themselves from unexpected changes in the price of oil) and others to engage in high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak market discipline incentives for major financial institutions.
It's like we're reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully hold investors in derivatives and repos responsible for the risks associated with their decisions when they make transactions with systemically vital financial institutions.
Au lieu de cela, we have survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
